Here's an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP. We'll use HTML for the front-end and PHP for server-side functionality.

**index.php**
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        /* add some basic styling */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Search Bar Example</h1>

<form action="" method="get">
    <input type="search" id="search-bar" name="query" placeholder="Enter search query...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<?php
if (isset($_GET['query'])) {
    // display search results here...

    $query = $_GET['query'];
    echo "You searched for: $query";
}
?>

</body>
</html>
```
In this example, we're using a simple `form` with an `input` field of type `search`. When the user submits the form (by clicking the submit button), the search query is sent to the server as a GET parameter named `query`.

**Server-side code:**
```php
// assuming you have a database connection set up...
$dsn = 'mysql:host=localhost;dbname=example';
$username = 'your_username';
$password = 'your_password';

try {
    $pdo = new PDO($dsn, $username, $password);
} catch (PDOException $e) {
    echo 'Connection failed: ' . $e->getMessage();
}

if (isset($_GET['query'])) {
    $query = $_GET['query'];
    // prepare and execute the search query
    $stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM example_table WHERE column_name LIKE :query");
    $stmt->bindParam(':query', '%' . $query . '%');
    $stmt->execute();

    // display search results
    echo "<h2>Search Results:</h2>";
    while ($row = $stmt->fetch()) {
        echo "<p>" . $row['column_name'] . "</p>";
    }
}
```
This code assumes you have a database connection set up and are using the PDO extension to interact with your database. The search query is prepared and executed as a SQL statement, using parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection.

**Tips:**

* Make sure to sanitize user input (the search query) before passing it to your database.
* Consider adding error handling and logging mechanisms to your server-side code.
* You may want to add more advanced features like pagination or filtering for larger datasets.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance.

